32:04.957 --> 32:06.456
I'm getting a little pepper.

32:06.959 --> 32:10.694
This still is just as smooth
as a reposado.

32:10.696 --> 32:14.865
<i>  This the perfect balance</i>
<i>  because I'm still getting</i>
<i>  a little bit of the tequila</i>

32:14.867 --> 32:17.167
and then a little bit
of vanilla flavor
from the oak.

32:17.169 --> 32:21.204
Very smooth but usually,
at the end of the day,

32:21.206 --> 32:24.174
I will always want
to come back to this.

32:24.176 --> 32:26.043
I think
at the end of all of this,

32:26.045 --> 32:27.911
I'm gonna go sit down
somewhere.

32:27.913 --> 32:29.546
[carlos laughs]

32:29.548 --> 32:33.083
meeting carlos and spending
some time with him
is really a honor,

32:33.085 --> 32:35.852
to sit with someone like this
with the experience
that he has.

32:35.854 --> 32:37.921
I know that you are traveling.

32:37.923 --> 32:40.590
There's other regions
in mexico
who produces spirits

32:40.592 --> 32:41.658
from agave.

32:41.660 --> 32:44.728
-Agave spirits.
-Tequila, mezcal,
bacanora, sotol.

32:44.730 --> 32:47.297
-It's all
from the agave plant?
-That is correct.

32:47.299 --> 32:49.333
Everything I've learned
about making tequila,

32:49.335 --> 32:51.802
I'm gonna bring that back home
to virginia.

32:51.804 --> 32:54.604
I'm gonna try
to incorporate that
into my technique.

32:54.606 --> 32:57.140
Well, I appreciate
the opportunity
to sit with you.

32:57.142 --> 33:01.578
And I also appreciate
you teaching me each region
that these come from.

33:01.580 --> 33:03.246
Cheers for that.

33:03.248 --> 33:04.815
<i> [tim] tequila is not</i>
<i>  the only thing</i>
<i>  you can make out of agave.</i>

33:04.817 --> 33:07.617
I'm going south.
I'm going
to mezcal country now.

33:07.619 --> 33:10.787
-And thank you for being here,
again, and again.
-Yes, thank you.

33:10.789 --> 33:11.989
-Thank you.
-Gracias.

33:25.204 --> 33:26.803
[mike] good old fresh,
sweet corn.

33:26.805 --> 33:29.172
[both grunt]

33:29.174 --> 33:33.110
yeah, we finally found
the sweet corn. We're ready
to get this stuff mashed in.

33:33.112 --> 33:34.911
[jerry] I love the sound
of that waterfall.

33:34.913 --> 33:36.079
[mike] it's nice, ain't it.

33:37.750 --> 33:39.149
There we go.

33:39.151 --> 33:41.151
<i>  Yeah, you know, we're not</i>
<i>  gonna grind this corn up.</i>

33:41.153 --> 33:45.589
We're just gonna take it
and shuck it and get
the kernels off the cob.

33:45.591 --> 33:50.127
Then we can mash it all in the
barrel, cobs, kernels and all.

33:52.731 --> 33:54.064
It has a worm or two in it.

33:54.066 --> 33:55.298
[jerry] don't leave
them in there.

33:55.300 --> 33:56.700
[mike] well that
just goes to tell you,

33:56.702 --> 33:59.136
there ain't been
no poisons or nothing
sprayed on this corn.

33:59.138 --> 34:02.105
<i>  And I worked with it</i>
<i>  in this barrel, and it's</i>
<i>  sticky, damn it's sticky.</i>

34:02.107 --> 34:03.573
And it's sweet as sugar.

34:03.575 --> 34:05.742
<i>  When we eventually run this</i>
<i>  through the 'still,</i>

34:05.744 --> 34:07.611
the flavor
that I'm looking for

34:07.613 --> 34:10.914
<i>  is the flavor that's going</i>
<i>  in to the mash barrel today.</i>

34:10.916 --> 34:13.250
You've got all your cream,
your cob flavor,

34:13.252 --> 34:14.818
everything going in to it.

34:14.820 --> 34:16.686
My grandma wouldn't
waste nothing.

34:16.688 --> 34:19.156
So if she had make cream corn,
she'd cream all these cobs

34:19.158 --> 34:20.991
and she'd turn it
and make corn cob jelly.

34:20.993 --> 34:23.293
-Corn cob jelly?
-Corn cob jelly.

34:23.295 --> 34:25.896
Some of the best jelly
you'll ever put in your mouth.

34:25.898 --> 34:26.930
I ain't never heard of such.

34:26.932 --> 34:29.900
I'll get my bride to make
some corn cob jelly.

34:29.902 --> 34:34.171
-[jerry] that'd be sweet.
-It will be sweet. For sure.

34:34.173 --> 34:35.605
-[mike] ready?
-[jerry] here we go.

34:36.308 --> 34:39.309
Easy does it. Yee-haw.

34:42.881 --> 34:45.082
All right,
all right, all right.

34:45.084 --> 34:47.884
Get her back up and I'll pour
a little sugar in here.

34:47.886 --> 34:49.920
Hey, this stuff
better damn work

34:49.922 --> 34:52.789
'cause it's the last sweet
corn I'm gonna find this year.

34:52.791 --> 34:54.391
<i>  Just keep it simple,</i>
<i>  make it happen,</i>

34:54.393 --> 34:55.859
and supply our customers.

34:55.861 --> 34:57.194
Lay the water to it.

34:57.830 --> 34:59.229
By god, I just
hit that right there

34:59.231 --> 35:01.465
it ain't gonna know
what to do with it.

35:06.004 --> 35:07.737
Now that our barrel's full
of good, fresh water,

35:07.739 --> 35:09.239
and our good sugar
and our good corn,

35:09.241 --> 35:12.109
now all we got left to do
is a pinch of yeast
and let her sit.

35:12.111 --> 35:14.711
All right, just pull down hard
on that side over there.

35:14.713 --> 35:15.946
All right, let me just find

35:15.948 --> 35:17.914
just a little something
to lay on top of it that--

35:17.916 --> 35:20.250
look at you, jer.

35:21.153 --> 35:22.986
Yeah! That'll work, won't it?

35:22.988 --> 35:25.255
Now that we got our mash all
in a barrel and ready to go,

35:25.257 --> 35:27.724
<i>  it makes me feel good that</i>
<i>  we got our 'still site set up</i>

35:27.726 --> 35:29.259
and I'm really
excited about it.

35:29.261 --> 35:31.027
Got another one mashed in,
ready to go.

35:31.029 --> 35:32.129
We made it happen.

35:32.131 --> 35:34.164
[jerry] well in 10 or 12 days,
we'll be back in here

35:34.166 --> 35:36.933
to get this run-off, make some
good, fresh corn squeezing.

35:36.935 --> 35:38.101
[mike] corn squeezing.

35:44.776 --> 35:46.243
[tickle] you know,
once I cut these soy beans,

35:46.245 --> 35:48.712
you won't ever even know
this ditch is here.

35:48.714 --> 35:50.914
Look, we might be able to
make some soy bean liqueur.

35:50.916 --> 35:52.115
That's what he told me
the other day,

35:52.117 --> 35:52.749
make some soy bean liqueur.

35:52.751 --> 35:53.950
It'd be good for you.

35:53.952 --> 35:56.786
You know, it's more protein
in there than it is anything.

35:56.788 --> 35:58.588
[henry] y'all can do whatever
you want with the soy bean.

35:58.590 --> 36:00.790
They fed me enough
of that stuff in prison.

36:00.792 --> 36:02.926
-I don't want any part of it.
-You want no part of it?

36:02.928 --> 36:04.895
[henry] the soy bean burgers,
soy bean hot dog,

36:04.897 --> 36:06.196
soy bean everything, man.

36:06.198 --> 36:07.597
[tickle] fine. We just
sell this stuff

36:07.599 --> 36:09.266
to people who ain't
been to prison.

36:09.268 --> 36:11.535
That's what I was gonna say.
Ain't everybody been
as much as we have.

36:14.773 --> 36:17.941
Well, tickle, this'll be
the last trip in ya, hoss.

36:17.943 --> 36:20.243
[henry] there'll be no more
driving a vehicle
in here after this run.

36:20.245 --> 36:21.878
Work everything
from the house, huh?

36:21.880 --> 36:23.013
Everything from the house.

36:23.015 --> 36:24.314
[tickle] I can work with that.

36:25.884 --> 36:28.185
We're gonna bring
the grain in today,

36:28.187 --> 36:31.188
<i>  mash in this still site,</i>
<i> and get this truck out of here</i>

36:31.190 --> 36:33.323
and there will be no more
vehicles coming down the hill.

36:33.325 --> 36:34.491
None.

36:35.160 --> 36:36.359
We gotta get
all this hooked up.

36:36.361 --> 36:38.028
No tire run
running it down here.

36:38.030 --> 36:39.029
You ain't kidding.

36:40.365 --> 36:41.898
There you go.

36:41.900 --> 36:44.267
Everything is coming together.

36:44.269 --> 36:46.236
<i>  They'll be running water</i>
<i>  from the house,</i>

36:46.238 --> 36:48.004
coming down our pipes
that we buried.

36:48.006 --> 36:50.140
<i>  I'm really excited</i>
<i>  to get this mash build in</i>

36:50.142 --> 36:52.842
<i>  and show the guys that</i>
<i>  we gonna do a mash build</i>

36:52.844 --> 36:54.711
that hadn't been done
in years and years and years.

36:54.713 --> 36:56.846
All right,
I better get the water on.

36:56.848 --> 36:59.249
It's gonna be an amazing,
amazing liqueur.

37:00.052 --> 37:01.218
[tickle] all right.

37:01.820 --> 37:04.054
We've got the water
turned on up at the house

37:04.056 --> 37:08.925
and we're filling these
stills up with nice,
clean, well water.

37:08.927 --> 37:11.294
There you go, kenny.
We got enough in that one.

37:11.296 --> 37:13.930
You know, this ground water is
the best water you can have.

37:13.932 --> 37:15.832
As soon as you
get that thing hooked up,

37:15.834 --> 37:19.269
we'll be back ready to
go ahead and chuck in
this stuff, hot.

37:19.271 --> 37:21.905
Right now we gotta
get the heat on these stills.

37:21.907 --> 37:23.707
Get this water boiling
so we can mash it.

37:23.709 --> 37:25.208
I rigged up this thing here.

37:25.210 --> 37:27.277
It's like an air hose
from a burner.

37:27.679 --> 37:28.845
You slide it on there.

37:29.014 --> 37:31.314
So now all I gotta do is tie
this end to the proper line.

37:31.316 --> 37:33.183
I just leave it in there.

37:33.185 --> 37:34.384
I'll run to
the top of the hill

37:34.920 --> 37:36.319
and turn the oil tank on.

37:37.022 --> 37:38.955
Yeah, we ready
to cooking some mash.

37:38.957 --> 37:40.223
All right, now we're ready?

37:40.225 --> 37:41.091
Let's see what we go.

37:41.093 --> 37:42.892
I kneel down,
I hook that baby up,

37:42.894 --> 37:45.395
I slide that burner in there
and I'm crossing my fingers.

37:48.100 --> 37:49.132
Yeah, baby.

37:49.134 --> 37:50.700
[kenny] heat both up
at the same time.

37:50.702 --> 37:52.102
[tickle] that's [bleep] sweet.

37:52.104 --> 37:55.772
We've got our oil burner
going, heating this water up.

37:55.774 --> 37:59.776
It's one nice, long flame
right underneath both stills.

37:59.778 --> 38:01.678
Now you're catching
the same amount of fuel,

38:01.680 --> 38:03.046
-but you're heating two.
-Heating two.

38:03.048 --> 38:06.950
Man, and I... It just
never crossed my mind
to do it like this.

38:06.952 --> 38:08.852
[henry] so what I want to do
is bring it to a good boil,

38:08.854 --> 38:11.655
then we throw that grain
in there, let that baby
cook for an hour.

38:11.657 --> 38:13.423
And then that's when
the magic happens.

38:13.425 --> 38:17.994
This recipe that I'm doing
here, it takes so much grain.

38:17.996 --> 38:19.929
It is unbelievable.

38:19.931 --> 38:20.697
It's a trick to it.

38:20.699 --> 38:22.265
I'll set the burner down.

38:22.267 --> 38:23.967
<i> [henry] you gotta get</i>
<i>  your water exactly right,</i>

38:23.969 --> 38:26.269
you've got to add the grain
at a certain time.

38:26.271 --> 38:28.905
<i>  You've got to know</i>
<i>  when to cover it over</i>
<i>  at a certain time.</i>

38:28.907 --> 38:31.241
Then comes
what we call sweetening it.

38:31.243 --> 38:33.576
What we're doing right here,
you see all this grain?

38:33.578 --> 38:35.879
You see all that corn?
That's just the beginning.

38:35.881 --> 38:38.014
Once we get this cooked in,
we will sweeten it

38:38.016 --> 38:40.283
with a special
malted barley blend.

38:40.285 --> 38:42.786
That's what's going to end up
some of the best liqueur

38:42.788 --> 38:45.355
that you'll ever,
ever stick your lips to.

38:45.357 --> 38:47.390
My family's been doing it
for generations.

38:47.392 --> 38:49.059
This is
carrying the heritage on.

38:49.061 --> 38:52.262
<i>  It's not only</i>
<i>  an old family recipe,</i>

38:52.264 --> 38:57.067
but there's another part
to this liqueur that really
makes it so good.

38:57.069 --> 38:58.268
[henry] this is
corn meal, hoss.

38:58.270 --> 39:00.570
-Okay, so it's a mixture.
-Mixture.

39:00.572 --> 39:02.772
It's the way
that it's being made.

39:02.774 --> 39:07.077
<i>  Each of these grains</i>
<i>  have got to be layered in</i>
<i>  one at a time</i>

39:07.079 --> 39:10.814
because this water
will take on these flavors

39:10.816 --> 39:15.919
differently depending on
what we put in first,
second, third, whatever.

39:15.921 --> 39:17.487
[kenny] this is malted barley.

39:17.489 --> 39:19.823
[henry] all right, here's
the trick, you gotta put this
just the right amount.

39:19.825 --> 39:22.025
Yeah, stir it in
real good, kenny.

39:22.027 --> 39:24.327
All right, now.
One more little magic trick.

39:24.329 --> 39:28.365
-Ah! Oh, I see
the secret ingredient.
-Yeah.

39:28.367 --> 39:30.934
-Wheat ranch. Hmm.
-Ah! Don't say it
too loud, man.

39:30.936 --> 39:35.038
[tickle] well, uh, henry gets
a little crazy when it comes
time to pitch the yeast.

39:35.040 --> 39:37.173
He says the mash goes
to talking to him

39:37.175 --> 39:39.642
and he can hear it and, uh...

39:39.644 --> 39:42.045
Um, the only time it goes
to talking to me

39:42.047 --> 39:45.248
is after we're done and I'd
drink about a half a quart.

39:45.250 --> 39:46.216
Wait, what?
What's that you're saying?

39:46.218 --> 39:48.017
Wait, what it saying?
"I'll be ready"?

39:48.019 --> 39:50.720
No, she said, "henry,
put a jacket on right now."

39:50.722 --> 39:53.957
it's starting to get cold
in the evenings now.

39:53.959 --> 39:56.793
<i>  So, uh, we're covering it</i>
<i>  with insulation</i>

39:56.795 --> 39:59.162
<i>  and then throwing a layer of</i>
<i>  black paper over top of that.</i>

39:59.164 --> 40:01.297
This is the only way
you can make liqueur

40:01.299 --> 40:03.099
when your temperature
starts getting down.

40:03.935 --> 40:06.936
[henry] to do a mash build
like this, kenny,
after all these years?

40:06.938 --> 40:09.406
[kenny] it's been a long time
since you made anything
like this at home.

40:09.408 --> 40:10.240
[henry] oh, believe it.

40:10.242 --> 40:11.775
<i>  It's been a great week,</i>
<i>  you know.</i>

40:11.777 --> 40:14.811
We took all this time
to make sure we got
everything built right,

40:14.813 --> 40:16.980
bound to head on out,
get a plan together.

40:16.982 --> 40:19.315
We'll be back four
or five days to run in vegas.

40:19.317 --> 40:21.151
-[tickle] I think
we're done here.
-[henry] I think we're done.

40:21.153 --> 40:22.252
[tickle] what do
you think, henry?

40:22.254 --> 40:24.254
-[henry] I think
we're done, son.
-[tickle] all right.

40:34.032 --> 40:35.965
[tim] you can see
those mountains over there.

40:35.967 --> 40:39.269
Looks a little bit different
than mountains of tennessee,
I can tell you that.

40:40.572 --> 40:42.906
You know, I've been
a long ways all over mexico.

40:42.908 --> 40:44.908
<i>  I've been to tequila.</i>
<i>  I went to arandas.</i>

40:44.910 --> 40:47.844
<i>  But right now, we're</i>
<i>  on our way to oaxaca, mexico.</i>

